1
00:00:00,521 --> 00:00:01,953
They detained me in this room

2
00:00:03,099 --> 00:00:04,453
I stayed for a day
and left the next day

3
00:00:08,021 --> 00:00:12,370
I was in this place, we
were about 30 prisoners in it

4
00:00:14,349 --> 00:00:16,302
I mean, a lot of
people were here

5
00:00:17,865 --> 00:00:18,880
In the room

6
00:00:18,905 --> 00:00:19,948
Interviewer: 30 people?

7
00:00:19,973 --> 00:00:21,641
About 30 people

8
00:00:23,958 --> 00:00:29,323
But you come in and see people
going out and coming in from here

9
00:00:29,844 --> 00:00:32,344
And then it’s someone
else’s turn to go out

10
00:00:32,969 --> 00:00:36,172
I mean, they take them
out and bring others in

11
00:00:38,438 --> 00:00:42,448
Interviewer: When you came in, what
did you talk about with the people here?

12
00:00:42,473 --> 00:00:44,498
We exchanged
greetings and I just sat

13
00:00:44,523 --> 00:00:46,727
And each one had a case

14
00:00:47,691 --> 00:00:51,076
Most of them were about
IDs and evidentiary documents

15
00:00:51,597 --> 00:00:54,957
Like if you had argued
with them or pushed them

16
00:00:55,972 --> 00:01:00,842
I mean, the light
sentences are here

17
00:01:00,894 --> 00:01:02,196
Not the heavy ones

18
00:01:02,665 --> 00:01:06,754
I came in here, they threw
me in, closed the door, and left

19
00:01:07,352 --> 00:01:08,602
So I sat here

20
00:01:08,707 --> 00:01:12,612
They asked, What’s your case? I said, It’s
to pick up my ID because I argued with them

21
00:01:12,637 --> 00:01:13,446
So they brought me here

22
00:01:14,748 --> 00:01:18,108
Interviewer: Where were you sitting?
Witness: I was sitting here

23
00:01:18,524 --> 00:01:21,701
Right here in this spot

24
00:01:24,323 --> 00:01:26,615
Interviewer: What was your
impression when you entered here?

25
00:01:26,640 --> 00:01:28,947
My impression was
that it was a prison

26
00:01:29,598 --> 00:01:31,525
You wait anxiously to get out

27
00:01:32,906 --> 00:01:36,578
Just because of my ID—I
hadn’t done anything

28
00:01:36,864 --> 00:01:38,713
Just because they
took my ID from me

29
00:01:42,723 --> 00:01:46,785
Interviewer: The time
you spent was one day

30
00:01:46,810 --> 00:01:47,539
Yes

31
00:01:50,145 --> 00:01:54,208
Interviewer: How did you spend your time with
the prisoners? What did you talk about?

32
00:01:54,233 --> 00:01:58,712
Were you afraid
of some prisoners?

33
00:01:59,286 --> 00:02:01,057
You’re afraid to talk about them

34
00:02:01,082 --> 00:02:03,947
To be honest, you’re
afraid to talk about them

35
00:02:04,338 --> 00:02:05,614
To say this or that

36
00:02:05,903 --> 00:02:08,611
Because there are informants
among them you don’t know

37
00:02:09,705 --> 00:02:13,116
I mean, you can’t talk
about them or curse them

38
00:02:13,455 --> 00:02:18,454
Because they place an
informant among the prisoners

39
00:02:19,054 --> 00:02:21,423
To find out what
you said about them

40
00:02:22,048 --> 00:02:25,304
Like if you say, Tomorrow
the army will come and free us

41
00:02:25,824 --> 00:02:30,408
Or you say, conditions will return
to the way they were before ISIS

42
00:02:31,371 --> 00:02:34,939
You can’t talk because there are
secret informants among the prisoners

43
00:02:35,278 --> 00:02:38,142
The moment you speak,
they will pass it on to them

44
00:02:38,845 --> 00:02:42,126
We talk about other things,
how they brought you and why

45
00:02:42,830 --> 00:02:44,991
And what’s your charge,
and you, what’s your charge

46
00:02:45,173 --> 00:02:46,736
And I told them it
was for a personal ID

47
00:02:48,089 --> 00:02:49,756
I had given a woman a ride alone

48
00:02:54,495 --> 00:02:57,933
Interviewer: Did they forbid
talking inside the room?

49
00:02:57,958 --> 00:03:00,563
No, you can talk
but not about them

50
00:03:01,500 --> 00:03:05,849
I mean, you talk and
get to know the others

51
00:03:05,874 --> 00:03:09,756
But you can’t talk about ISIS

52
00:03:12,620 --> 00:03:17,255
Interviewer: What sounds did you
hear while you were inside this room?

53
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:18,636
And how was the
smell of the place?

54
00:03:18,792 --> 00:03:23,688
The smell of sweat and the
smell of people in the prison

55
00:03:24,599 --> 00:03:28,428
Some of them had been here
for a week, or four days, or three

56
00:03:28,862 --> 00:03:32,716
And there were no
showers for bathing

57
00:03:33,288 --> 00:03:36,544
In fact you only went to
the washrooms once a day

58
00:03:40,346 --> 00:03:45,086
Interviewer: Is there a story you remember, whether
funny or sad, that happened to you inside the prison?

59
00:03:45,111 --> 00:03:51,752
In that situation everyone was sad.
Who would be happy in those days?

60
00:03:52,117 --> 00:03:53,836
Everyone had had
their fill of oppression

61
00:03:54,435 --> 00:03:56,466
I mean, look where we
were and where we’d ended up

62
00:03:57,221 --> 00:04:01,753
Anyone would be
crushed by what had happened

63
00:04:02,638 --> 00:04:06,414
I mean, you enter a detention center
and get imprisoned over an ID card

64
00:04:07,178 --> 00:04:11,448
Now if you argue with a policeman he
hands you your ID and tells you to go

65
00:04:11,473 --> 00:04:13,063
But those people had no mercy

66
00:04:13,401 --> 00:04:14,990
They were not
merciful with people

67
00:04:23,766 --> 00:04:29,704
Interviewer: You said you’re a smoker. How
could you go a whole day without smoking?

68
00:04:29,729 --> 00:04:32,204
You can put up with that

69
00:04:33,037 --> 00:04:36,109
You are forced to

70
00:04:36,266 --> 00:04:39,131
I mean, they can prevent
you from having a cigarette

71
00:04:47,490 --> 00:04:50,381
Interviewer: How many
people were with you?

72
00:04:50,406 --> 00:04:52,204
We were about thirty people here

73
00:04:58,401 --> 00:04:59,964
Interviewer: Do you
remember any of them?

74
00:05:00,433 --> 00:05:05,563
They were folks from Mosul—people
from the villages and countryside

75
00:05:05,954 --> 00:05:09,209
And from inside Mosul, some were
from the right bank and the left bank

76
00:05:09,860 --> 00:05:14,911
If I saw him now I’d recognize
the face of the one who was with me

77
00:05:16,318 --> 00:05:17,985
Interviewer: Didn’t
you make friends?

78
00:05:18,010 --> 00:05:23,141
You can’t do that
in a day or two

79
00:05:23,166 --> 00:05:25,667
We just exchanged
greetings, and I sat in this spot

80
00:05:26,251 --> 00:05:28,048
And they all sat
lined up like this

81
00:05:28,543 --> 00:05:31,616
And when you sleep the place
gets crowded with rows of sleepers

82
00:05:32,449 --> 00:05:34,481
Interviewer: In which
row did you sleep?

83
00:05:34,506 --> 00:05:38,413
I was here next to the window
where there was only a small opening

84
00:05:38,647 --> 00:05:39,949
I was sleeping here

85
00:05:39,974 --> 00:05:42,007
And the person’s
feet were toward you

86
00:05:42,032 --> 00:05:45,235
We were lined up
almost one after another

87
00:05:48,491 --> 00:05:50,470
Interviewer: Was it
winter or summer?

88
00:05:50,495 --> 00:05:52,788
No, summer—around July

89
00:05:53,257 --> 00:05:55,679
At that time, in the heat

90
00:05:57,632 --> 00:05:59,376
And there was
only this ceiling fan

91
00:06:01,043 --> 00:06:02,684
Interviewer: Wasn’t there an air-conditioning unit?
Witness: What?

92
00:06:02,736 --> 00:06:02,996
Wasn’t there an
air-conditioning unit?

93
00:06:03,307 --> 00:06:04,636
I mean cooling

94
00:06:04,819 --> 00:06:07,085
There was no cooling

95
00:06:08,009 --> 00:06:11,264
Air conditioners, I
mean—no, there weren’t any

96
00:06:11,475 --> 00:06:12,908
Just this fan

97
00:06:21,267 --> 00:06:28,532
Interviewer: What were the charges
against the prisoners who were with you?

98
00:06:28,557 --> 00:06:30,902
Here they kept those
with light sentences

99
00:06:31,840 --> 00:06:34,210
They didn’t have heavy sentences

100
00:06:34,705 --> 00:06:36,033
These were light sentences here

101
00:06:39,069 --> 00:06:41,960
Interviewer: Also
cigarette charges?

102
00:06:41,985 --> 00:06:44,668
Yes, cigarettes and a quarrel

103
00:06:45,241 --> 00:06:48,027
And for the IDs, those kinds
of things that happened here

104
00:06:49,277 --> 00:06:53,548
Most of the charges were
about arguing with them

105
00:06:54,277 --> 00:06:56,439
And you’d spend
two or three days

106
00:06:58,106 --> 00:06:59,173
And get flogged

107
00:06:59,929 --> 00:07:03,106
Interviewer: How was the
relationship among you prisoners?

108
00:07:03,132 --> 00:07:05,554
The relationship
was good among us

109
00:07:08,652 --> 00:07:12,793
Just a group sitting in a
prison, talking and laughing

110
00:07:13,444 --> 00:07:15,293
Yes, but you couldn’t smoke

111
00:07:15,918 --> 00:07:17,350
And you couldn’t talk about them

112
00:07:18,219 --> 00:07:24,547
Because you feared the undercover
informant would pass on your words

113
00:07:25,198 --> 00:07:27,724
He would go and tell them,
so-and-so is talking about you

114
00:07:29,886 --> 00:07:32,750
Interviewer: Did you
feel there was a spy?

115
00:07:32,829 --> 00:07:37,230
There is—in every prison they have an
undercover informant, but you don’t know who

116
00:07:38,011 --> 00:07:41,735
I mean, among those thirty, one of them
is the informant, but you don’t know which

117
00:07:42,073 --> 00:07:43,662
And he’s the one
who gets you talking

118
00:07:44,678 --> 00:07:46,657
He tries to trap
you into talking

119
00:07:47,073 --> 00:07:49,808
So people knew there was a spy

120
00:07:50,771 --> 00:07:52,282
But he never reveals himself

121
00:07:54,053 --> 00:07:58,557
Interviewer: Were these windows
closed or completely open?

122
00:07:58,582 --> 00:07:59,782
Only this opening

123
00:07:59,807 --> 00:08:01,822
Just this one for ventilation

124
00:08:03,593 --> 00:08:05,234
For ventilation

125
00:08:05,963 --> 00:08:08,176
Those are windows

126
00:08:10,390 --> 00:08:11,562
Interviewer: And this?

127
00:08:11,587 --> 00:08:14,608
This one is also closed, and
the upper part was for ventilation

128
00:08:15,286 --> 00:08:16,692
This one was completely closed

129
00:08:20,416 --> 00:08:22,447
There was only
one for ventilation

130
00:08:23,671 --> 00:08:25,312
And these windows are closed

131
00:08:26,223 --> 00:08:29,973
And up here there’s
only a spot for ventilation

132
00:08:29,998 --> 00:08:32,525
Just so they could
breathe in these rooms

133
00:08:34,114 --> 00:08:36,432
Interviewer: Do you
remember anyone dying here?

134
00:08:37,656 --> 00:08:41,249
No, no one died here

135
00:08:41,279 --> 00:08:43,075
I stayed one night and left

136
00:08:43,234 --> 00:08:45,838
I didn’t stay for days or a week

137
00:08:50,682 --> 00:08:53,624
Interviewer: Was anyone
tortured in this room?

138
00:08:53,649 --> 00:08:56,229
No, they didn’t beat
anyone in front of me

139
00:09:03,286 --> 00:09:06,489
Interviewer: Does this
blanket remind you of anything?

140
00:09:12,348 --> 00:09:14,354
I haven’t seen it before

141
00:09:14,874 --> 00:09:18,702
The floor was clean
and we sat directly on it

142
00:09:19,119 --> 00:09:20,213
There were no mattresses

143
00:09:21,515 --> 00:09:23,364
There were none in this hall

144
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:26,454
The tiles were clean
and we sat on them

145
00:09:27,573 --> 00:09:30,334
You slept and sat on the tiles

146
00:09:30,359 --> 00:09:34,240
Sometimes you’d sleep while sitting—if
there wasn’t space, you slept sitting

147
00:09:36,610 --> 00:09:39,136
Interviewer: Was any
prisoner sentenced to death?

148
00:09:39,161 --> 00:09:41,532
No, here the charges were light

149
00:09:42,313 --> 00:09:47,313
Anyone sentenced to death was
taken somewhere else, another prison

150
00:09:50,438 --> 00:09:54,683
Interviewer: Was there a screen
to show ISIS videos in this room?

151
00:09:54,839 --> 00:09:57,209
No, there was no TV
screen for ISIS videos

152
00:10:09,875 --> 00:10:13,677
Interviewer: Did prisoners
write memories on the wall?

153
00:10:13,702 --> 00:10:18,078
Anything they try
to write on the wall

154
00:10:18,443 --> 00:10:20,109
We don't have a
pen or anything else

155
00:10:20,134 --> 00:10:22,115
They search you, empty your
pockets, and then they send you in
